Dear all,

Sorry I closed issue #808 since after some profiling I figured out the dominator of the performance penalty is the `substitute` method. I pasted a screen capture of my tool, after running around 20 mins. As you can see from the figure below, the `com.microsoft.z3.Native.INTERNALsubstitute` method takes almost 90% of the total execution time. Note that since our tool can actually run for hours or days, I can expect the `substitute` function would eventually takes almost 100% of the execution time.. 

<img width="1130" alt="screen shot 2016-11-27 at 1 36 22 am" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5838310/20646110/fb085866-b441-11e6-9715-02daf539844a.png">

So given a path condition (e.g, `symbol1 * 4 + symbol2*2 + 12 > 0`) what I am trying to do is 1) collect all the symbols in the formula (i.e., `symbol1` and `symbol2` for this case) 2) substitute each with a fresh symbol and produce a new formula (e.g., substitute `sym` into `sym_new`, and the sample formula would become `symbol1_new * 4 + symbol2_new * 2 + 12 > 0`) 3) put both original and the new formula into the solver to check the satisfiability regarding those symbols. Note that the  number of path condition formulas could be over hundreds.

I then write the following `Scala` code for the above procedure:  Note that variable `sbl` is the list of each symbol and corresponding fresh new symbol, for example, `sbl = List(("symbol1", "symbol1_new"), ("symbol2, symbol2_new"))`. This list is built in the `build_symbol_pair' function.


     def add_path_conditions(m: Solver, pcs: List[BoolExpr], sbl:  List[(BitVecExpr, BitVecExpr)], en: Engine) = {
        pcs.foreach { (pc) =>
          m.add(pc.asInstanceOf[BoolExpr])
          val pc1: Expr = sbl.foldLeft(pc.asInstanceOf[Expr]) { (pc0, sb) => pc0.substitute(sb._1, sb._2) }
          m.add(pc1.asInstanceOf[BoolExpr])
        }
      }

    def build_symbol_pair(en: Engine, kl: List[BitVecExpr]): List[(BitVecExpr, BitVecExpr)] = {
        kl.map(k =>
          (k, en.ctx_z3.mkBVConst(k.toString + "n", k.getSortSize))
        )
     }

Conceptually, I don't see any obvious issue with the above code, besides each time `substitute` one symbol may not be the most efficient way. But it seems that currently the `substitute` function is just quite slow for some reason.. 

So I am writing to ask, given my situation (i.e., substitute one or multiple symbols), is there any way that can speed up the substitution process? I would really appreciate for any advice and suggestion. Thank you!

Sorry to bug you. I've a question about calling inherited python class method. In this example.cpp file, I have one abstract class `Entity`, and a method `get_top_entity_path` that expects an `Entity`:

```c++
#include <iostream>

#include <pybind11/operators.h>
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

using namespace std;
using namespace pybind11;

class Entity {
public:
    Entity();
    virtual ~Entity();

    virtual std::string get_segment_path() const = 0;
    virtual std::string get_entity_path(Entity *ancestor) const = 0;

    Entity* parent;
    std::string name;
    std::string parent_name;
};

Entity::Entity() {}
Entity::~Entity() {}

class PyEntity: public Entity {
public:

    using Entity::Entity;

    std::string get_entity_path(Entity* ancestor) const override {
        PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(
            std::string,
            Entity,
            get_entity_path,
            ancestor
        );
    }

    std::string get_segment_path() const override {
        PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(
            std::string,
            Entity,
            get_segment_path,
        );
    }

};

std::string get_top_entity_path(Entity & entity) {
    std::cout << "entity = " << &entity << std::endl;
    std::cout << "entity.name = " << entity.name << std::endl;
    std::cout << "entity.parent_name = " << entity.parent_name << std::endl;
    std::cout << "entity.get_segment_path() = " << entity.get_segment_path() << std::endl;
    if (entity.parent == nullptr) {
        std::cout << "entity.get_entity_path(nullptr);" << std::endl;
        return entity.get_entity_path(nullptr);
    }
    std::cout << "get_top_entity_path(*entity.parent);" << std::endl;
    return get_top_entity_path(*entity.parent);
}


PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example)
{
    module ex("example", "test example");
    module types = ex.def_submodule("types", "types module");

    class_<Entity, PyEntity>(types, "Entity")
        .def(init<>())
        .def("get_segment_path", &Entity::get_segment_path)
        .def("get_entity_path", &Entity::get_entity_path)
        .def_readwrite("parent", &Entity::parent)
        .def_readwrite("name", &Entity::name)
        .def_readwrite("parent_name", &Entity::parent_name);

    ex.def("get_top_entity_path", &get_top_entity_path);

    return ex.ptr();
};
```
methods `get_entity_path` and `get_segment_path` are pure virtual, and in the python script I try to inherit this `Entity` class and try to execute this `get_top_entity_path` method:

```python
import example

class A(example.types.Entity):
    def __init__(self):
        self.parent = None
        self.name = "name-a"
        self.parent_name = "parent-name-a"

    def get_segment_path(self):
        return "segment-path-a"

    def get_entity_path(self):
        return "entity-path-a"

a = A()
print example.get_top_entity_path(a)

```

And I got segfault both in linux(ubuntu 14.04) and mac(10.10.4). Is it a valid way to use pybind11? Did I miss something? Could I call method of inherit class defined in python script from C++ side like this?


